    <h1>Shopping Cart Demo: Floating-Point Arithmetic Issues</h1>
    <p>This demo shows how floating-point arithmetic in JavaScript can cause problems when handling decimal prices, like $4.99. We'll build a simple shopping cart with two versions:</p>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>Broken Version:</strong> Uses native floating-point numbers, demonstrating incorrect totals and failed comparisons with the triple-equals (===) operator.</li>
        <li><strong>Corrected Version:</strong> Uses integer arithmetic (storing prices in cents) for precise calculations.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Explanation of the Problem</h2>
    <div class="section">
        <p>JavaScript uses floating-point numbers (IEEE 754 standard) to represent decimals. This can lead to precision errors because not all decimal fractions can be represented exactly in binary. For example:</p>
        <ul>
            <li>Adding 0.1 + 0.2 doesn't equal exactly 0.3; it equals approximately 0.30000000000000004.</li>
            <li>When comparing prices with the triple-equals (===) operator, these tiny errors can cause unexpected failures (e.g., 4.99 === 4.99 might sometimes return false due to rounding).</li>
